<title>
We Know All About You by Rhodri Jeffreys-Jones review – the dangers of our surveillance society
</title>
<link>
https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/22/we-know-all-about-you-rhodri-jeffreys-jones-review
</link>
<description>
<p>A readable history of snooping in Britain and US argues that private spying organisations have done as much harm as the state<br></p><p>When the US government contractor <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/edward-snowden">Edward Snowden</a> disclosed the extent of the global eavesdropping operation being run by the National Security Agency, GCHQ and their partners in Australia, Canada and New Zealand, many people spoke, aghast, of the way in which the 21st century appeared to have ushered in a new age of surveillance.</p><p>Yet spying on a mass scale has of course been with us for as long as governments have been skittish about foreign powers or uncertain about the loyalties of their own citizens. When Oliver Cromwell established the Post Office as a state monopoly in 1657, he did so not because he wished to improve England’s communications, but because the opening of mail was considered to be “the best means to discover and prevent any dangerous and wicked designs against the Commonwealth”.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/22/we-know-all-about-you-rhodri-jeffreys-jones-review">Continue reading...</a>
