<title>
Che, My Brother by Juan Martin Guevara review – the making of a revolutionary
</title>
<link>
https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/16/che-my-brother-juan-martin-guevara-review
</link>
<description>
A sibling’s affectionate account of the formative years of Che Guevara offers a compelling insight<p>One could argue that sufficient ink has been expended on Che Guevara. Those who fought with him, including <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/oct/28/biography.features">Fidel Castro</a>, have written memoirs, and there’s a definitive biography by the reporter who located Che’s body, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Lee_Anderson">Jon Lee Anderson</a>. But, as Anderson himself says, wherever there is revolt or resistance, there is still that face: of the hero-revolutionary Bolivian nuns called “San Ernesto”. And there still exists an insatiable desire for more about the man behind the T-shirt or poster, especially when it comes from his family.</p><p>Ernesto Guevara, “El Che”, was 15 when his younger brother Juan Martin was born, about to set off on the first of his adventures, by electrically powered bicycle, then motorbike, then the boat Granma, on which he sailed from Mexico to help ignite and lead the Cuban revolution.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/16/che-my-brother-juan-martin-guevara-review">Continue reading...</a>
