<title>
Virginia Wolf by Kyo Maclear and Isabelle Arsenault review – the ‘Bloomsberry’ girls
</title>
<link>
https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/mar/21/virginia-wolf-isabelle-arsenault-kyo-maclear-childrens-book-of-the-week
</link>
<description>
<p>This clever picture book imagines the secret world of the young Virginia Woolf and her sister Vanessa. And doesn’t shy away from tackling depression</p><p>The novelist <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/dec/05/100-best-nonfiction-books-no-45-a-room-of-ones-own-by-virginia-woolf-shakespeares-sister-seton-beton" title="">Virginia Woolf</a> once described the <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/feb/15/vanessa-and-her-sister-priya-parmar-review" title="">bond she shared with her sister</a>, the <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2017/jan/27/design-and-desires-how-vanessa-bell-put-the-bloom-in-bloomsbury" title="">artist Vanessa Bell</a>, as a “close conspiracy”. When she took her own life in 1941 she left two suicide notes behind: one for her husband and one for her beloved Vanessa.</p><p>Now with beautiful splashes of colour and witty, uplifting text, the Canadian duo Kyo Maclear and illustrator Isabelle Arsenault imagine the secret childhood world the sisters created, while delicately exploring the theme of depression, in this exceptional picture book for ages 4+, finally published in Britain after its acclaimed release in Canada in 2012.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/mar/21/virginia-wolf-isabelle-arsenault-kyo-maclear-childrens-book-of-the-week">Continue reading...</a>
