<item>
<title>
Howard Jacobson: ‘Trump in the White House – that must never feel normal’
</title>
<link>
https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/02/howard-jacobson-pussy-interview-trump-in-white-house-must-never-feel-normal
</link>
<description>
<p>In the early hours as the US election result became apparent, the novelist was at his desk beginning his satirical novel about the president, Pussy. He’s angry, frustrated – and don’t tell him to get over it</p><p>From the moment Donald Trump <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/16/donald-trump-announces-run-president">announced he was running for president</a>, the flood of words about the orange-faced reality-TV star and alleged property billionaire has been incessant. And it only increased after he actually became president. But those words have been factual, or at least purport to be factual, no matter how absurd and unbelievable the Trump story has often appeared. What no one has done is write fiction about this most fictional of real-life characters. Until now.</p><p>I thought he’d be shot or impeached before his inauguration</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/02/howard-jacobson-pussy-interview-trump-in-white-house-must-never-feel-normal">Continue reading...</a>
</description>
