<title>The 100 greatest novels of all time: The list</title>
<link>
https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/oct/12/features.fiction
</link>
<description>
From Don Quixote to American Pastoral, take a look at the 100 greatest novels of all time<br /><br /><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2011/jun/14/100-greatest-non-fiction-books">The 100 greatest non-fiction books</a><br /><br /><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/aug/17/the-100-best-novels-written-in-english-the-full-list">The 2015 version of the 100 best novels</a><p><strong>1. Don Quixote</strong> Miguel De Cervantes<br>The story of the gentle knight and his servant Sancho Panza has entranced readers for centuries. <br><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/dec/13/classics.miguelcervantes">• Harold Bloom on Don Quixote – the first modern novel</a></p><p><strong> 2.</strong> <strong> Pilgrim's Progress</strong> John Bunyan<br>The one with the Slough of Despond and Vanity Fair. <br><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/sep/23/100-best-novels-pilgrims-progress">• Robert McCrum's 100 best novels: The Pilgrim's Progress</a></p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/oct/12/features.fiction">Continue reading...</a>
